## The problem with Gas
:::

::: {.content-visible unless-format="revealjs"}
### The problem with Gas
:::

Look at what SNAIVE and Drift produce for Gas:

::: {.fragment}


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code  code-fold="true"}
gas_fc |>
  filter(.model %in% c("snaive", "drift")) |>
  autoplot(
    aus_production |> filter_index("2000 Q1" ~ .),
    level = 95
  ) +
  facet_wrap(~ .model, nrow = 2) +
  labs(
    title = "Gas — benchmark forecasts with 95% prediction intervals",
    y = "Petajoules", x = NULL
  )
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](model_diagnostics_files/figure-revealjs/gas-pi-raw-1.png){width=960}
:::
:::


:::

::: {.fragment}

Both models produce intervals of **constant width** — they assume forecast variance stays the same across all periods. But the series shows growing variance: the swings in the 2000s are far larger than those in the 1970s. The intervals are miscalibrated.

:::

# Forecasting with transformations

::: {.content-hidden unless-format="revealjs"}
## The residuals tell the story
:::

::: {.content-visible unless-format="revealjs"}
### The residuals tell the story
:::

From the residual diagnostics we ran in [1.3](../03_fcst/forecasting.qmd), SNAIVE on Gas showed non-constant variance — larger residuals in recent decades, smaller in earlier ones. That is the signature of **multiplicative** behavior: the seasonal swings are proportional to the level of the series.

::: {.fragment}


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code  code-fold="true"}
gas_fit |>
  select(snaive) |>
  gg_tsresiduals() +
  labs(title = "Gas — SNAIVE residuals")
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](model_diagnostics_files/figure-revealjs/gas-resid-reminder-1.png){width=960}
:::
:::


:::

::: {.fragment}

As we saw in [1.2](../02_ts_dcmp/ts_dcmp.qmd), a Box-Cox transformation stabilizes the variance. Applied here, the model fits in the transformed scale and `fable` back-transforms the forecasts automatically.

:::

::: {.content-hidden unless-format="revealjs"}
## Choosing $\lambda$
:::

::: {.content-visible unless-format="revealjs"}
### Choosing $\lambda$
:::


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
lambda <- aus_production |>
  features(Gas, features = guerrero) |>  #<1>
  pull(lambda_guerrero)                  #<2>

lambda
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] 0.1095171
```


:::
:::


1. `guerrero` is a named feature function in `feasts` — pass it directly to `features()`.
2. Extract the scalar value so it can be reused in model specs.

::: {.content-hidden unless-format="revealjs"}
## Fitting models with Box-Cox
:::

::: {.content-visible unless-format="revealjs"}
### Fitting with Box-Cox
:::

Wrap the response variable in `box_cox()` inside the model spec:

::: {.fragment}


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
gas_fit_bc <- gas_train |>
  model(
    snaive_bc = SNAIVE(box_cox(Gas, lambda)),       #<1>
    drift_bc  = RW(box_cox(Gas, lambda) ~ drift())  #<2>
  )
```
:::


1. Box-Cox applied inside the spec — the model sees stabilized variance.
2. Same transformation for Drift. Both use the same `lambda` estimated above.

:::

::: {.fragment}


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
gas_fc_bc <- gas_fit_bc |>
  forecast(h = nrow(gas_test))
```
:::


:::

::: {.content-hidden unless-format="revealjs"}
## Intervals before and after transformation
:::

::: {.content-visible unless-format="revealjs"}
### Intervals before and after
:::

The intervals are computed in the transformed scale and then back-transformed. Because $e^x$ is a convex function, the back-transformation stretches the upper tail more than the lower one — the resulting intervals in the original scale are **asymmetric**.

::: {.panel-tabset}

## Without transformation


::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](model_diagnostics_files/figure-revealjs/gas-pi-no-bc-1.png){width=960}
:::
:::


## With Box-Cox


::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](model_diagnostics_files/figure-revealjs/gas-pi-bc-1.png){width=960}
:::
:::


:::

::: {.content-hidden unless-format="revealjs"}
## Accuracy after transformation
:::

::: {.content-visible unless-format="revealjs"}
### Accuracy after transformation
:::

Does the transformation improve forecast accuracy?


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
